\f0\fs26\fsmilli13333 \cf3 the profound mixture of culture and language and the way in which pain and exploitation are experienced so unequally. 
\f1\fs24 \

\f0\fs26\fsmilli13333 Starting from the Cuban revolutionary 
\f1\i radionovela 
\f0\i0 and its expansion throughout Latin America, telenovelas have turned into opportunities to invent stories, to imagine lives, to seek deliverance, to punish the baddies, to participate in the reinterpretation, to encourage personal encounters and seek new forms of communication. 
\f1\fs24 \

\f0\fs26\fsmilli13333 Unknowingly and without intending to leave a televisual or audiovisual record, Latin-American audiences have been creating \'93transmedia\'94 expansions permanently. This symbiosis between audiences and telenovelas lives on beyond the moment of watching a screen; it has gained expression in private and public life, with relatives, neighbors and coworkers (Mart\'edn-Barbero et al., 1992). What happens on television is transformed into the audiences\'92, if not legal, then cultural property, since they process information, relating it with their own lives and conferring it new meanings (Orozco, 2014a). 
\f1\fs24 \

\f0\fs26\fsmilli13333 Fiction on television is the one genre that attracts both the most financial investment and the most audiences. This investment is not just via production and advertising costs. It also takes the form of product placement and political and commercial propaganda within the stories (Orozco & Franco, 2011). Venezuela under Chavismo and Mexico under the 
\fs24 pri 
\fs26\fsmilli13333 (Partido Revolucionario Institucional) are prototypes of such investment. For example, propaganda expenditures in fiction in Mexico, which we could label as \'93political 
\f1\i merchandising
\f0\i0 ,\'94 surpassed 205 million dollars in 2012; much more than political parties spent in formal publicity in their campaigns (Fundar Centro de An\'e1lisis e Investigaci\'f3n, 2015). 
\f1\fs24 \

\f0\fs26\fsmilli13333 As in other regions, television in Latin America is diversifying its products and the ways to access them, making their programs available from smartphones, and creating the new genre of very short 
\f1\i webnovelas 
\f0\i0 that preserve the emotional intensity of their predecessors, but adapting it to the format so as to make them compatible with the audiences\'92 current circumstances, devices and expectations; but for the popular classes, the old model continues to be the most important one (Orozco, Hern\'e1ndez, Franco & Charlois, 2012). 
