\i\fs26\fsmilli13333 \cf3 Although authors that represent the Anglo-Saxon approach, such as 
\f0\i0 \cf3 Katz (2009) (see also Carey, 2005; Carl\'f3n & Scolari, 2014; 
\f1\i \cf3 Friedman, 2013; 
\f0\i0 \cf3 Piscitelli, 2010
\f1\i \cf3 ) underscore 
\f0\i0 \cf3 technological breakthroughs as the main causes for the changes in television, Latin-American authors pay more attention to the social practices that favor TV audiences (Orozco, 2014c; Orozco & Miller, 2016). 
\f1\fs24 \cf3 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sl320\sa240\partightenfactor0

\f0\fs26\fsmilli13333 \cf3 We think that beyond its political-economic base, the success of television lies in its essentialist ontology: people believe in the evidence presented on the screen. They make out in it the spoken and seen reality, allied, paradoxically, to the fantasy world of television and its openness to the viewers\'92 self\'96insertion (Orozco, 2014c). The classically denotative, apparently non-interpretative notion of television reality continues to be valid (Scolari, 2013; Hall, Hobson, Lowe & Willis, 1980). 
\f1\fs24 \

\f0\fs26\fsmilli13333 This experience has reached its peak in the last two decades, both in Latin America and in Western Europe and the USA. According to this, the population has been the object of \'93audienciaci\'f3n\'94
\fs18\fsmilli9333 \up5 6 
\fs26\fsmilli13333 \up0 (turning into audiences) in ways that alter the rest of everyday life (Orozco, 1996). Being the audience means connecting with others and the other in a mediated way through the screens, which results in the fact that what we know is not the object itself, but its representation on the screen. 
\f1\fs24 \

\f0\fs26\fsmilli13333 These forms of knowledge are now mixed also and they live on as \'93mass self communication\'94 (Castells, 2009). What was previously a centralized form of communication still matters, but it can be personalized for more individual experiences. This new tendency cause new forms of experiencing the televisual to coexist with old forms of mass media-audiences relations, and its textuality and cultural resonance in the Americas, we believe, will be decided largely by their audiences\'92 magical realism, mestizaje and \'93solitudes\'94
\f1\i , 
\f0\i0 just as it has been historically. 
